The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 Three employees of an oil refinery in Budge Budge were allegedly beaten up on Wednesday by Citu men. The injured workers were admitted to a local hospital.

 he union has been pressuring the owner of the refinery to appoint its members as regular employees. Three complaints had been lodged by the owner with police. Rivalry between unions was behind the incident, said cops. Citu leaders denied involvement in the violence. They said local goons had been terrorising the owner and the workers of the refinery.

 The Left Front civic board?s proposal to waive interest and penalty on property tax dues for the Dunlop premises at 62A, Mirza Ghalib Street and 46B, Chowringhee Road was passed in the House on Wednesday. The dues and water charges on the two premises total more than Rs 18 lakh. The owners will have to cough up only Rs 9 lakh.

 nder pressure from the Trinamul Congress, mayor Bikash Ranjan Bhattacharyya submitted details of the dues before the House. He assured the Opposition that if the company tries to sell off the units after the waiver grant, then the civic body will not allow the properties to be mutated. 

 Mayor Bikash Ranjan Bhattacharyya has ordered verification of some files processed during the tenure of his predecessor Subrata Mukherjee. The order follows a government audit report that has pointed out anomalies in the files. The mayor said a probe might be ordered.

 Four men, aged between 19 and 23 years, were arrested on Wednesday for robberies in the New Market, Sudder Street and Chandni Chowk area. Last month, the youths allegedly broke into a lodge near New Market and took away goods worth about Rs 40,000. The leader of the gang had cleared ICSE from a school on Park Street and is fluent in English.

 Singapore Airlines on Wednesday announced a new economy class fare of Rs 14,000 (without taxes) to key destinations in Southeast Asia from the city. Those availing of the offer can stop over at Singapore both on the way to and back from Kuala Lumpur, Penang or Langkawi. 

 Large parts of south Calcutta suffered power failures over the past two weeks following damage to CESC underground cables during digging of roads by the civic body. Other parts of the city suffered power cuts due to overloading and theft of transformer parts.

 Police are on the lookout for a man named Shan Ali in connection with the rape of a 16-year-old girl on New Tangra Road on Monday.

 Teenagers Mousumi Das and Pinky Saha, residents of Barasat, went missing on Tuesday night after a party to celebrate Mousumi?s birthday. 

